<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: 72 to 60 pin EXP 6 to Famicom Sound Out mod]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11677&amp;p=134472#p134472"><![CDATA[
You'll need to cut the jumper and replace it with a resistor in order to get audio mixed in from the NES side.<br />The simplest mixing circuit was that used by the N163-using boards: it was just a 5-20kΩ resistor from AUDIO FROM 2A03 to AUDIO TO RF, with the output from the 163 connected to AUDIO TO RF. Drilling a little hole and adding a potentiometer would be a reasonable thing to do.<br /><br />The <a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/File:MMC5_audio.png" class="postlink">MMC5</a> and <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?p=101695#p101695" class="postlink">SS5B</a> both used a very similar and more complicated circuit.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3512">lidnariq</a> — Tue Sep 30, 2014 12:50 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
